<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="1489" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1489">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 855.48/237</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the</hi>
                            <gloss type="to">
                                <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State</hi>
                            </gloss>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-06">
                                    <hi rend="italic">April 6, 1915</hi>.</date>
                                <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 7, 7 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1989. Department’s 1423. Foreign Office replies that military authorities
                            unaware of any attack on <hi rend="italic">Elfland</hi> on 21st. If any
                            mistake <pb facs="1294" n="1036" xml:id="pg_1036"/> in identity were
                            made it must be ascribed to exceptional difficulty of work of submarines
                            and aeroplanes. They are minutely informed regarding markings and
                            movements of commission’s ships. Government recommends that horizontal
                            markings on deck of ships be erected. Copy note mailed Hague and
                            commission.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>